                        </StackPanel>

                        <TextBlock TextWrapping="WrapWholeWords" Margin="0,10"> 
                            Notice there are 14 tiles. 
                            A winning hand always gets it's last tile as it's draw tile (self-drawn), or by stealing another player's discard.
                        </TextBlock>


                        <TextBlock Text="Stealing a Discard" 
                                   Margin="0,20,0,5" 
                                   Foreground="{ThemeResource MahjongAccentColorBrush}" 
                                   FontWeight="SemiBold" 
                                   FontSize="22" />

                        <TextBlock TextWrapping="WrapWholeWords" Margin="0,10"> 
                            If someone discards a tile at the end of their turn, and that tile completes a set or is the winning tile for another player's hand, they might be able to steal the tile. 
                            Discards that complete a Pung (set of three of a kind) or Kong (set of four of a kind) can be stolen by anyone at the table. 
                            When a tile is stolen, the player who stole must lay down their set face up and discard a tile. 
                            Play then continues from that player. This often results in someone being skipped.) 
                        </TextBlock>

                        <TextBlock TextWrapping="WrapWholeWords" Margin="0,10"> 
                            Discards that complete a Chow (run of three) can only be stolen by the player to the right of the discarder. 
                            Basically, the stolen tile just replaces their draw tile. 
                            They must lay the Chow down face up, then play continues normally. 
                        </TextBlock>

                        <TextBlock TextWrapping="WrapWholeWords" Margin="0,10"> 
                            When a player steals to complete a Kong, they must lay the Kong down face up, then draw a tile from the Dead Wall, then discard.
                        </TextBlock>

                        <TextBlock TextWrapping="WrapWholeWords" Margin="0,10"> 
                            When a player is ready to go out and win the round, they can steal their final Mahjong tile from anyone's discard.
                        </TextBlock>

                        <TextBlock Text="Concealed Tiles" 
                                   Margin="0,20,0,5" 
                                   Foreground="{ThemeResource MahjongAccentColorBrush}" 
                                   FontWeight="SemiBold" 
                                   FontSize="22" />

                        <TextBlock TextWrapping="WrapWholeWords" Margin="0,10"> 
                            At the beginning of a round, a player's whole hand is concealed (hidden from everyone else). 
                            Here are some reasons why parts of it might be revealed throughout the game. 
                            This is important, because concealed sets are worth more, and a concealed or partially-concealed hand earns extra points at the end of the round for the winner. 
                        </TextBlock>
                        
                        <TextBlock TextWrapping="WrapWholeWords" Margin="0,10"> 
                            If a player steals a discard to complete a pung, chow, or kong, that set must remain revealed for the rest of the round. 
                        </TextBlock>
                        
                        <TextBlock TextWrapping="WrapWholeWords" Margin="0,10"> 
                            If a player completes a Kong by drawing the tile, the Kong is technically concealed for scoring purposes, but they must reveal it to the other players. 
                            This is done by laying the Kong out with other revealed sets, but keeping the first and last tile concealed. 
                        </TextBlock>
                        
                        <StackPanel Orientation="Horizontal">
                            <FontIcon FontFamily="Segoe UI Emoji"
                                      Glyph="&#x1F02B;" 
                                      Margin="0,0,5,0"
                                      FontSize="30" />
                            <FontIcon FontFamily="Segoe UI Emoji"
                                      Glyph="&#x1F005;" 
                                      Margin="0,0,5,0"
                                      FontSize="30" />
                            <FontIcon FontFamily="Segoe UI Emoji"
                                      Glyph="&#x1F005;" 
                                      Margin="0,0,5,0"
                                      FontSize="30" />
                            <FontIcon FontFamily="Segoe UI Emoji"
                                      Glyph="&#x1F02B;" 
                                      FontSize="30" />
                        </StackPanel>

                        <TextBlock TextWrapping="WrapWholeWords" Margin="0,10"> 
                            Any time a player completes a Kong, they must draw a tile from the Dead Wall to account for the extra tile their hand now requires.
                        </TextBlock>

                        <TextBlock TextWrapping="WrapWholeWords" Margin="0,10"> 
                            If a winning player's hand is concealed, but their final Mahjong tile is stolen from another player's discard, then the winning hand is partially-concealed earning them 10 points. 
                            If they draw the winning tile from the wall, then the hand is fully concealed earning them a double.
                        </TextBlock>


                        <TextBlock Text="Other Ways to Win" 
                                   Margin="0,20,0,5" 
                                   Foreground="{ThemeResource MahjongAccentColorBrush}" 
                                   FontWeight="SemiBold" 
                                   FontSize="22" />

                        <TextBlock TextWrapping="WrapWholeWords" Margin="0,10"> 
                            Collecting sets and a pair is the normal way to go out and win a Mahjong round. 
                            But there are other, weirder ways to win. 
                            There's often risk involved here, since you'd have to change which tiles you're collecting. 
                            But they result in big points. 
                            Here an example ofone such hand, called Kokushi musou (国士無双), aka "Thirteen Orphans". 
                            It consists of one of each terminal and honor tile, plus one extra to make any pair.
                        </TextBlock>


                        <StackPanel Orientation="Horizontal" Margin="0,0,0,15">
                            <FontIcon FontFamily="Segoe UI Emoji"
                                      Glyph="&#x1F000;" 
                                      Margin="0,0,5,0"
                                      FontSize="25" />
                            <FontIcon FontFamily="Segoe UI Emoji"
                                      Glyph="&#x1F001;" 
                                      Margin="0,0,5,0"
